tools

Class ShellExpansionAnalyzer<S>

  • java.lang.Object
    • tools.ShellExpansionAnalyzer<S>

  • public class ShellExpansionAnalyzer<S>
extends java.lang.Object
    A tool for determining some basic numerical quantities pertaining to a given IndexedNavigableRootedNeighborGraph, tabulating these quantities for display in a JTable, and saving the data to a file.

    Before tabulating or saving any data, the data must first be created by calling the method generateData(). This method determines the following:
        (i) The number of vertices and edges of the graph.
       (ii) Whether or not the graph is bipartite.
      (iii) The length of the shortest cycle based at the root.
      (iv) The maximum distance from the root among all vertices of the graph.
    In addition, three arrays of length one more than the maximum distance of item (iv) above are created:
       (ai) An array s_n, whose i-th entry is the number of vertices of distance i from the root.
      (aii) An array e_n, whose 0-th is 0, and whose i-th entry is the number of edges joining the shells of radius i and i-1, centered at the root.
     (aiii) An array t_n, whose i-th entry is the number of edges whose endpoints are both of distance i from the root.

    Remark: This tool is primarily intended to be used for graphs which are known to be vertex-transitive (meaning that for every pair of vertices of the graph, there is a graph symmetry carrying one vertex to the other), in particular the Cayley graphs. In this case, item (iii) is the girth of the graph, item (iv) is the diameter, and the three arrays above are independent of the root.
    Author:
    pdokos

      • generateData

        public void generateData()
        Generates all of the numerical data pertaining to the graph. More specifically, this method determines the following:
            (i) The number of vertices and edges of the graph.
           (ii) Whether or not the graph is bipartite.
          (iii) The length of the shortest cycle based at the root.
          (iv) The maximum distance from the root among all vertices of the graph.
        In addition, three arrays of length one more than the maximum distance of item (iv) are created:
           (ai) An array s_n, whose i-th entry is the number of vertices of distance i from the root.
          (aii) An array e_n, whose 0-th is 0, and whose i-th entry is the number of edges joining the shells of radius i and i-1, centered at the root.
         (aiii) An array t_n, whose i-th entry is the number of edges whose endpoints are both of distance i from the root.

      • getBasicDataTableModel

        public final javax.swing.table.TableModel getBasicDataTableModel()
        Creates a basic data TableModel. This is a single-row, five-column TableModel, with columns labeled by: "Vertices", "Edges", "Bipartite", "Diameter", "Girth".

        Note that the labels "Diameter" and "Girth" reflect the intent that the graph is actually vertex-transitive, as explained in the description of this class. If it is not the case that the graph is vertex-transitive, then the meaning of the quantities associated with these properties are as described in items (iii) and (iv) in the description of this class.

        Returns:
        An basic data TableModel.

      • getVertexShellTableModel

        public final javax.swing.table.TableModel getVertexShellTableModel()
        Creates a vertex shell TableModel. This is a five-column TableModel with the first three columns labeled by: "n", "|S(n)|", "|S(n)|/|S(n-1)|", and the last two columns blank. The rows run from n=0, 1, ..., maxDistance from root. The entry in the third column of the first row is set to null.
        Returns:
        An vertex shell TableModel.

      • getEdgeTableModel

        public final javax.swing.table.TableModel getEdgeTableModel()
        Creates an edge shell TableModel. This is a five-column TableModel with the following labels: "n", "|E(n)|", "|E(n)|/|E(n-1)|", "T(n)", "|E(n)|/|S(n)|". The rows run from n=1, ..., maxDistance from root. The entry in the third column of the first row is set to null.
        Returns:
        An edge shell TableModel.

      • writeBasicDataToFile

        public boolean writeBasicDataToFile(java.io.File f)
                             throws java.io.IOException
        This method writes a single line text file containing the following five integer values separated by single spaces: (1) number of vertices, (2) degree, (3) diameter, (4) girth, (5) bipartite (a boolean value represented by 0 or 1).

        The second entry actually contains the size of the set of neighbors of the root. For a vertex-transitive transitive graph, this is the degree.

        Parameters:
        f - The file to which the data is written
        Returns:
        true if the data was successfully written to file.
        Throws:
        java.io.IOException

      • writeRadialDataToFile

        public boolean writeRadialDataToFile(java.io.File f)
                              throws java.io.IOException
        This method writes the three arrays s_n, e_n, and t_n to a text file (see items (ai), (aii), and (aiii) in the class description for the definitions of these arrays). The entries are written to the file as a line-separated sequence of triplets of integers, the i-th triplet of the list containing the i-th entries of the three arrays in the order listed above (separated by single-spaces).
        Parameters:
        f - The file to which the data is written
        Returns:
        true if the data was successfully written to file.
        Throws:
        java.io.IOException
